               <p>1345. <persName id="def1-1345-18430403" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1345-18430403" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1345-18430403" type="age" value="48"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1345-18430403" type="surname" value="JARVIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1345-18430403" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS JARVIS</hi>
                  </persName>, was indicted<rs id="t18430403-1345-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430403-1345-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430403-1345-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18430403-cd-211" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430403-1345-offence-1 t18430403-cd-211"></join>20th of March</rs>, 200lbs. weight of lead, value 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18430403-name-1264" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1264" type="surname" value="HAYLES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1264" type="given" value="ROBERT FORD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430403-1345-offence-1 t18430403-name-1264"></join>Robert Ford Hayles</persName>; and fixed to a building.—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, not stating it to be fixed.—4 other <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNTS</hi>, stating it to be the property of <persName id="t18430403-name-1265" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1265" type="surname" value="HUBBARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1265" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430403-1345-offence-1 t18430403-name-1265"></join>William Hubbard</persName>, and William and <persName id="t18430403-name-1266" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1266" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1266" type="surname" value="HUBBARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1266" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430403-1345-offence-1 t18430403-name-1266"></join>Sophia Hubbard</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-1267" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1267" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1267" type="surname" value="BUCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1267" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BUCK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable F</hi> 124.) On Sunday evening, the 19th of March, my attention was attracted to a house, No. 2, Bedfordbury, in the parish of St. Martin-in-the-fields—some bricks had fallen from the cornice-work—on the following Monday I went and examined the state of the lead, it was coiled up when I first saw it, but would require cutting before it could be taken away, and the place where the lead had been was vacant—I saw the prisoner at the window—he was within reach of this lead—I went round my beat, and returned about twenty minutes past six o'clock—I then noticed that the lead was beaten out, and flattened down to its place—I came again at half-past seven o'clock—I saw a truck, and the prisoner brought a barrel out of the house, put it into the truck, and pushed the truck round to King William-street, from the front of the house, and left it there—I looked at it, and found the barrel contained some lead—it was much heavier lead than that which I had noticed before—I then saw the prisoner at the barrel—I asked him what he had there—he said "Nothing, it is my own pro<lb></lb>perty"—I was not satisfied, and took him to the station—I went back to the house, went on the roof, and found the dormer had been stripped of lead—the cornice was left as it was—there were four nail-holes in the lead.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184304030169"></xptr>
               <p>and there were four nails on the dormer—they appeared to correspond with the holes—I measured them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> King William-street is some distance from Bedfordbury? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About half a quarter of a mile—I was standing at the corner of Chandos-street, and Bedfordbury, when he drew the truck away from the door—he had an opportunity of seeing me—I have not had any conversation with anybody who has got up this prosecution, since I was before the Magistrate—I went to Mr. Humphreys the same evening—my evidence was written down before the Magistrate—I did not mention at Mr. Humphreys', for the first time, that I had been to the house, and ex<lb></lb>amined the lead—it was before the Magistrate—I believe I said at Mr. Humphreys', for the first time, that I saw the prisoner move the truck into the back-street—I followed behind him when he was drawing the truck—he had left the truck for about a moment, when I examined it—I did not see where he went to—he did not tell me he was going to have the lead recast—it was at Mr. Humphreys' I first mentioned about the nail-holes—Mr. Elliott was not there at the time—I did not see him there at all—I went to the house afterward—I was in my police dress—my examination before the Magistrate was read over to me—I stated that it contained all I wished to say.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Mr. Humphreys is the solicitor for the prosecution? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I attended there, and had my examination taken down—I was desired by Mr. Humphreys to come to his office.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-1268" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1268" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1268" type="surname" value="HUBBARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1268" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HUBBARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the husband of a lady whose name was Sophia Hayles—she was a widow, and I married her, fourteen or fifteen years ago—she had a son by her first marriage—he is not of age—I and my wife have re<lb></lb>ceived rent for this house in Bedfordbury since our marriage—there was for<lb></lb>merly a tenant named Spronton there—when he went out he let the prisoner in—the prisoner has paid me rent—I have had very great difficulty in getting it from him, and have been obliged to seize his goods several times—at last I was obliged to bring an action in my own name—I have not received any<lb></lb>thing in consequence of that action.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> The prisoner has been in the house twelve years, I believe? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About eleven—I hold the title deeds of this house—the title to it has not been in dispute, to my knowledge—I went to Mr. Humphreys, at the last examination—I was before the Magistrate the day the prisoner was committed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-1269" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1269" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1269" type="surname" value="ELLIOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1269" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ELLIOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. James Taylor, who is agent to this property—this house belongs to the son of Mrs. Hubbard before her marriage—he is heir-at-law—Mr. Hubbard and his wife have been in the receipt of the rents since their marriage—an action was brought for use and occupation in consequence of not getting the rent—I attended at the Master's office to tax the costs—the prisoner appeared in his own behalf—the costs were taxed at 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and some odd shillings—the prisoner said he was not prepared to pay the amount, he should want time—I told him there was a large arrear of rent due, and he had better give up the premises—he said he was willing to do so—I told him Mr. Hubbard, I had no doubt, would make a great sacrifice if he would give up the possession of the property; he might give it up at Lady-day—he said he would.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long is it since you first received rent of the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between ten and eleven years—he was not to put the house in order, or repair it—I was to write to Mr. Hubbard to know what he would take off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-1270" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1270" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1270" type="surname" value="BUCKLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1270" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BUCKLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a plumber, in Bath-street, City-road. I prepared</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184304030170"></xptr>
               <p>the lead-work for the repair of this house in Bedfordbury some years ago—I have examined this lead—I got into the house the first time after the lead was removed—I noticed the dormer window on the roof—I have since seen the lead in possession of the officer, and, in my judgment, it was taken from the place—I have measured the nails and nail-holes, and it exactly corresponds—I went with the lead to the house, and they refused to let us in—there is about a hundredweight and a half of lead gone—this is not more than three-quarters of a hundredweight—this piece is worth 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and the whole perhaps 21<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—it would cost a great deal more to replace it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> But if that had been re-cast, with a little more, and replaced, it would cost less? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It would depend on the substance—I knew nothing of the premises before the repairs in 1836.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Does this appear to require re-casting? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—it would have lasted fifteen or twenty years.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
